{"product_id": "33230", "page": 40, "page_order": 5, "recommended": false, "date": "2017-10-12", "text": "Probably my first and last Assassin's Creed game. There isn't much to say about this game. The gameplay is terrible, the story aweful.\nWhile the beginning can actually be quite pleasant, the game long overstays its welcome. The last part is a slug full of insipide filler missions and leading to an overwhelmingly disappointing ending.\nThe controller support is shameful. Don't even consider playing the game with anything else than the 360 controller. Any other controller will involve spending an inordinate amount of time fiddling with Steam controller remaping options and yes that includes the xbox one controller.\nAvoid.", "hours": 31.9, "username": "BenB", "products": 168, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 40, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-10-12", "text": "No comment 10/10", "hours": 29.9, "user_id": "76561198088742040", "username": "\u272fTsiqman\u272f", "products": 83, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 40, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-10-11", "text": "Assassin's Creed was the first title to not only employ, but invent the Ubisoft formula. It featured sheer infinite content compared to the first game and a lot more to do to break monotony during story progression. Revisiting AC2 more than seven years later I have to admit it still hasn't lost a single ounce of its charm.\nMost of the equipment is entirely optional, but there's a lot of versatility in AC2 which AC1 was desperately lacking.\nAssassin's Creed 2 might not be a masterpiece, but it is a milestone of gaming history. And it does pick up more and more with Brotherhood and Revelations, which are the second and third entries of the Ezio trilogy.", "hours": 77.1, "user_id": "76561197969749884", "username": "Sarkoth", "products": 1470, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 40, "page_order": 8, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-10-10", "text": "I enjoyed this one a lot.  There was plenty of variety with the missions, locations and puzzles.  The Italian Renaissance setting was awesome, and I thought the voice acting was very well done.  Using real historical characters, cities, architecture and art created a very immersive atmosphere and educated at the same time.  A definite step up from the first one (although I don't remember AC1 that well.)\nThere are no dialog options, and the only progression elements are better weapons/armor/items and more money, so this is not an RPG.  It's more like a third-person action/puzzle game with a good story and a great setting.\nThere were some wtf?/really? moments but overall a great game.  Highly recommended.  9/10", "hours": 54.9, "user_id": "76561198036187439", "username": "gspot19", "products": 1105, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 40, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-10-09", "text": "Capped at 60 fps no matter what. Nonetheless still very good", "hours": 18.1, "username": "Enyx", "products": 22, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 41, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-10-09", "text": "Assassin's Creed 2 is a well-aged open-world action game with an epic storyline and immersive environment.  The graphics have held up surprisingly well over time; though the cutscenes certainly look dated.  I completed the game (not 100% collection) in around 25 hours.  The free-running aspect of the game feels intuitive after a little practice.  There's a good mix of platforming and combat.  Amazingly, uPlay isn't even that annoying anymore.\nI did experience one desktop crash, but the game loaded right back to where I was when it happened.  The keyboard/mouse controls can be a little awkward (WASD vs. joystick) and presenting controls as symbols instead of buttons is frustrating until you get used to them.  Going for 100% completion is very repetetive; there are a lot of unmapped collectibles and generic assassionation/race contracts.\nOverall, I highly recommend this game in 2017.  The main quest is enough, though.  There's no real need to seek out a 100% completion.  Search the internet for  the completion cutscenes and save yourself hours of searching for collectibles!", "hours": 25.1, "username": "DFCSpeck", "products": 113, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 41, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-10-08", "text": "the best assassins creed ever , great story , great gameplay and awesome mechanic , dont know how Ubisoft screwed this franchise after this master peice", "hours": 23.0, "user_id": "76561198084149917", "username": "jammin", "products": 33, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 41, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-10-07", "text": "PROS:\n+addictive completion motivation/lots of collectables\n+Interestin story/concept\n+satisfying assassin/parkour abilities\nCONS:\n-CONTROLS UGH\n-a bit dated graphics\n-some obvious plotholes/glaring flaws with story\n-boring middle part of game\nI picked this up from the recent Assassin's Creed sale on Steam. I decided to buy the Ezio collection (2/Brotherhood/Revelations) because I never finished 2 on the console years ago. Hearing people claim this to be the best one has me worried for playing future installments as I would barely rate this a recommendation.\nBy far the biggest frustration for me was the controls. As a disclaimer, I played using an Xbox 360 controller. I dont know if it is better using KB/Mouse, but I figured since there is no real aiming needed, and its a console port, a controller is a safer bet. Well, I would say about...80% of the time Ezio did what I wanted him to do. The other 20% I was usually screaming at my monitor saying, \"WTF are you doing Ezio??!?!\" The game has a lot of timed sections, as well as tense moments when your fighting with guards. Having Ezio do something you dont want him to do can be REALLY annoying. To extrapolate on this, I'm fairly certain I took more damage from falling than from fighting over the course of the entire game.\nAlso the story. There were many times were it was just plain bad. One instance comes to mind is you are met with a problem of you needing a ticket to take a boat. Immediately upon knowing this a woman starts yelling for help: she is stuck on an island. You get a boat, and take her back to land. It turns out she just happens to be the owner of the castle? Like wtf? Why is the baroness of the entire area stranded on an island randomly? The entire middle part of the game is just fluff and errands. I feel like the game could have been told in a portion of the time and have done much better. Also in a reation to the story, Ezio felt really lifeless. Aside from the first few hours when his character is built up, the game does nothing to really make you care about him, hes essentially a lifeless killing machine.\nThats a lot of negative points. What about the positive? Well the parkour and animations are done well (when it works). The game does a good job (when it works) of making you feel like a badass stealthy assassin. Also, it feels like the classic mechanics that invented it all, the type of fighting and movement systems you see in more recent games (Batman and Shadow of Mordor) so its fun to experience the \"grandfather\" of these type of mechanics.\nThe graphics are also starting to show their age by modern standards. I was delighted to have the game work and look good (for its age) on my 4k monitor, but the graphics just look bland and foggy. Leftover console port issues I'm assuming.\nOverall, I recommend AC2 to experience the origins of Ezio's story, but I will not be doing a second playthrough. It was too frustrating with the controls.", "hours": 29.2, "username": "Synik", "products": 242, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 41, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-10-07", "text": "Never played any of the AC series before so I went online to check which ones had the best reviews to buy on the sales last week. AC II was the one I started with but the controls seem sooo weird.. They seem like they were made for a console (maybe xbox) and then transferred really poorly to PC. I'll try to memorise them and play the game cause it seems really promising but it still is frustrating!", "hours": 2.5, "user_id": "76561198086683467", "username": "WannaBeFree", "products": 128, "found_funny": 2, "early_access": false}
