{"product_id": "33230", "page": 399, "page_order": 8, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-07-28", "text": "Title:\n\"Assassin's Creed II\"\nDeveloper(s)/producer(s):\nUbisoft Montreal/Ubisoft\nWriter(s):\nCorey May\nJoshua Rubin\nJeffrey Yohalem\nGenre(s):\nAction-adventure, Stealth\nMode(s):\nSingle-player\nGeneral info:\nAssassin's Creed II is a 2009 historical fiction action-adventure open world stealth video game, the second major installment in the Assassin's Creed-series.\nIt is a direct sequel to Assassin's Creed (2007) and follows Desmond Miles as he relives the genetic memories of another of his ancestors through the use of the \"Animus\".\nGameplay:\nThe player directly controls the character through a third-person perspective, and can control the camera allowing for a 360\u00b0 view of their surroundings. The game takes place in an open world environment with nonlinear gameplay, allowing the player to roam freely within several regions throughout late fifteenth-century Italy such as Venice, Florence, Forl\u00ec, San Gimignano, and the Tuscan countryside.\nThe \"Animus 2.0\", a new version of the machine of the same name present in the previous game, provides in-game context for changes and additions to several game elements. A database is also available, providing extra historical information about key landmarks, characters and services that the player encounters.\nThe health system has been made more dynamic, with synchronization to the Animus and causing the character to recover only from minor injuries. More grievous injuries require visiting a street-side doctor or use of medicine (which can be purchased from doctors or found on bodies).\nThe player can now swim in water (which was not possible in the first game) and \"Eagle Vision\" - the ability to identify specific people and landmarks - can now be used in third-person view and while moving.\nThe player can row gondolas, as well as ride horses at any point in the game where they are readily available between towns and cities. The combat system is more complex than that of its predecessor, with the ability to disarm opponents using counter-attacks while unarmed.\nWeapons like swords, cutlasses, maces, axes and daggers can all be purchased from vendors in each city.\nThe player can also pick up any weapon on the ground or use improvised weapons, such as brooms or halves of a spear.\nIn addition, players are able to purchase artwork for their villa, obtain new armor as the game progresses, and even dye the character's clothing with a number of different colors. Other equipment includes larger pouches to carry more throwing knives and medicine.\nThere are several outlets for using currency, with vendors selling items such as medicine, poison, weapons, repairs, upgrades, paintings, and clothing dyes. When these shops are renovated, the player receives discounts at the shops on the goods they sell.\nThere is also a broadened array of methods for hiding or blending in an area. One can dive underwater to break guards' line of sight, and blending may be performed with any group of people, rather than only a specific type (as in the first Assassin's Creed). The game features a notoriety system, with guards more alert to the player's presence depending on their behavior, location, and current mission. This infamy can be reduced through bribery, removing wanted posters, or assassinating corrupt officials.\nStory:\nAssassin's Creed II begins immediately after the events of the first game.\nIn 2012, Desmond Miles is still trapped by Abstergo Industries (the modern-day face of the Knights Templar) after being forced to use the Animus device to revisit genetic memories of the Assassin Alta\u00efr Ibn-La'Ahad, and has discovered prophetic warnings from Subject 16 (a previous captive) describing the end of the world.\nHe is soon rescued by Lucy Stillman, a mole for the Assassins within Abstergo, who takes him to meet two other Assassins, historian Shaun Hastings and computer expert Rebecca Crane.\nThey request that Desmond use their version of the Animus, dubbed the Animus 2.0, to relive memories of another of his Assassin predecessors: Ezio Auditore da Firenze. Doing this is supposed to train Desmond in the ways of the Assassins through the \"Bleeding Effect\" of the Animus.\nEzio's memories begin during the Renaissance in the 15th century, where his family is ensnared in a mysterious political plot.\nAfter his father and brothers are executed for supposed treason, Ezio follows his father Giovanni's last advice, finds his father's Assassin tools, and flees the city with his mother and sister to the safety of his uncle Mario's villa in the countryside.\nMario assists Ezio in discovering the people behind the conspiracy, the search leading Ezio from Florence, to San Gimignano, Forl\u00ec, Venice and eventually to Rome.\nAs he identifies and assassinates more and more political figures, Ezio also gains several allies, including Niccol\u00f2 Machiavelli and Leonardo da Vinci - the latter of whom helps Ezio improve his equipment using schematics found in the old Codex pages of Alta\u00efr.\nEzio's long journey for vengeance and answers shape him into an efficient killing machine and as he gets closer to the truth - and the people responsible for his brother's and father's death - the great conspiracy only grows bigger and more confusing...\nMy opinions:\nI first played this game on the Playstation 3, immediately after it's release in November 2009.\nAfter finishing the first game almost a year earlier, the hype for this next installment of the series was very big.\nThis was one of the rare occassions were such extreme hype and expectation (especially for a Ubisoft-game) was NOT met with disappointment.\nI was hooked with the game for days straight and loved almost everything about it.\nIt felt much bigger, much more free and much more interesting than it's predecessor - all of which were because it WAS bigger, more free and had a more interesting story.\nExcept that the cities of Florence, Venice and Forl\u00ed offerred more diversity than Damascus, Jerusalem and Acre, the story also felt more intriguing and made me want to continue - want to know how Ezio's journey would end.\nSince this game - and possibly because of this game - I have bought every new Assassin's Creed-game, which are released on an annual basis nowadays.\nI would mainly recommend this game for people who have played it's predecessor.\nAlthough it is possible to start out with this game (since some brief explenations are made in the beginning), I highly recommend playing the first game before starting this much better sequel.\nAssassin's Creed remains my favourite franchise out of all video games to date and this is one of the series best installments.", "hours": 85.4, "user_id": "76561198029674280", "username": "ErikG96", "products": 709, "early_access": false}
