{"product_id": "33230", "page": 443, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-03-04", "text": "A magnificent game! The story gets a huge upgrade from AC1 and so do the graphics! Even Lucy is more beautiful than ever before.\nAll in all, AC2 is the main reason why the AC franchise got so popular. It definitely deserves all its popularity.", "hours": 20.9, "username": "Denolth", "products": 220, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 443, "page_order": 3, "recommended": false, "date": "2014-03-04", "text": "Evidently, I enjoyed the game enough to play it to completion; however, I don't feel I can truly endorse it.\nEven with a good gamepad, the controls are unwieldy, which turned what should have been a fun free-running romp into an unfortunate series of the player character leaping from ledges to his death whilst I attempted to sidle elsewhere.  Most of the game consisted of me screaming at Ezio to \"GO UP!! GO UP!!\"\nControl scheme aside, the game suffered from stale combat mechanics, repetitive tasks, boring assassinations (don't bother sneaking about; just make a b-line for your target, do the deed, and run away frantically), and repetitive tasks.  For a game about assassins, there were disappointingly few stealth tactics.\nFinally, my biggest frustration with modern games was displayed prominently in Assassin's Creed 2: Gameplay takes a backseat to the story.  If I wasn't stabbing those obnoxious lute players for my own twisted amusement, I was running to get from unskippable cutscene A to unskippable cutscene B... to unskippable cutscene C.  Frankly, I didn't find the story or its characters to be terrifically compelling.  For a noble's son, Ezio gains his aptitude for senseless killing suspiciously quickly.  And two games later, I'm still not sure why the Templars and the Assassins are forever at war, but I am sure that I don't care.\nI know I'm in the minority here, but AC2 is all about free-thinking and individuality.  Or something.  I wasn't really paying attention.\nEDIT: Oh, and for what it's worth, I didn't have any problems with Uplay.", "hours": 28.5, "username": "Supreme Loser", "products": 542, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 443, "page_order": 4, "recommended": false, "date": "2014-03-04", "text": "UPLAY.\nOne word which has destroyed the game for me. No to Spy/Ad/Malware aka Uplay.", "hours": 0.2, "user_id": "76561198054077892", "username": "Sanji", "products": 185, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 443, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-03-04", "text": "A huge improvement over the first game, Assassin\u2019s Creed II offers up an enormous, beautiful open world that\u2019s easy to get lost in, an epic storyline and all the fun that comes from creatively killing villains and tearing across 15th-century rooftops at ridiculous speeds.", "hours": 23.6, "username": "riccyxo", "products": 15, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 443, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-03-03", "text": "great game-the combat and stealth both got revamped! the stealth is A LOT harder now, but the combat makes up for it and the story is still its same awesome self + the fact that the assassin storyline in the animus is alot more engaging.\nnote: they also added an inventory, database, and shop systems that are to die for!", "hours": 430.6, "user_id": "76561198091413941", "username": "Causus", "products": 104, "early_access": false}
