{"product_id": "33230", "page": 477, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-12-01", "text": "Assassin's Creed 2 is one of the best of the Ezio trilogy (still doesn't beat AC Brotherhood in my opinion), enhancing the experience and errors the original had. The game has a much more charming and likeable protagonist named Ezio Auditore, and the mechanics have been greatly improved as well as having a way bigger world to play in.\nProblem is, the game does have some very tedious collecting, and some things still need improvement, but overall, this is a fantastic game, and shows potential that Assassin's Creed can do better.\nI give it 9 out of 10.\nBesides the two errors I mentioned, this is a fantastic game, and should not be missed.", "hours": 25.0, "username": "\u9f8d Mao", "products": 556, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 477, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-12-01", "text": "Better than the original, if I do say so myself.  There's just as much to do -- if not more (some of it tedious and unnecessary; like collecting flags).  The graphics alone are reason to play; the openness of the world and landscapes are absolutely breathtaking.  The gameplay and controls have been revamped ever so slightly, combat upgraded, and improved, but are still similar enough to the previous game that you can transition seemlessly from one game to the next.\nThe story continues in Rennaissance Italy from the perspective of the Assassin Ezio Auditore and you learn much more about the Assassins, the Templars, and the plot thickens...\nUnfortunately, the vastness of the world and the limited means of mobility (running, horseback, sparce waypoints) lead to a lot of time spent just travelling around and this can become tedious, but not enough to detract from the adventure.\n9/10", "hours": 37.1, "username": "Crono", "products": 222, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 477, "page_order": 8, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-12-01", "text": "Best game in the series! But see to it that you play them all in order.", "hours": 44.7, "username": "AxiAl Fundo", "products": 122, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 477, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-12-01", "text": "Assassin's Creed 2 is the best game of the series. The environment is the best, the gameplay is fun, and the character Ezio is so adored his story got expanded two more games.\nIf you're looking for a way in to the series, this is the game.\nI do want to point out two big things: the investment feels rather tangential, but has to be done to get better armor and weapons. Eventually you will have too much money and not enough useful things to spend it on.\nI dislike having to also open up Ubisoft's gaming client. That's a rather nitpicky issue, but it means if I want to play this game offline, I better have opened up Ubisoft's gaming client beforehand.", "hours": 247.8, "username": "CCooper1994", "products": 276, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 478, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-11-29", "text": "Pretty good, yo.", "hours": 67.5, "username": "Jennifer!", "products": 442, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 478, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-11-29", "text": "Open world Parkour & Assassination game. Modern day sections of the game suck and the Ancient World content is brilliant: it makes complete sense when Desmond (the main protaganist) wants to go back to Italy.\nVoice Acting, Story, Dialogue, Characters and Combat are all good. Campaign is lengthy. There is a vast amount of content/sidequests and a reasonable amount of variety. The aged graphics are still good because of the attention to detail and no \"uncanny valley\".\nGamepad strongly recommended. Get it on sale.", "hours": 1.2, "user_id": "76561197971532050", "username": "Conditional Love", "products": 688, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 478, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-11-29", "text": "Been playing games for over 30 years, this was one of the few times I was excited to play like when I was younger.", "hours": 246.9, "user_id": "76561197985224359", "username": "Oreb", "products": 210, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 478, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-11-29", "text": "A massive improvement over the first game, AC2 improves upon the original in every possible way: story, gameplay, characters, setting, and more. Renaissance Italy is full of fun and violence, and this game brings you right into the middle of both. The silly future/present day storyline continues, but thankfully it takes a backseat most of the time and lets you stay with Ezio: one of my favorite player characters of recent years. There's a ton of content here, the combat is greatly improved, there is less tedium (like the side-missions in the first game) and more murdering to do, and all taking place in some massive and beautiful locations. If I had to say negative stuff (and I do), it's that the villa management stuff is rather annoying and the platforming dungeons can, at times, be extremely frustrating. This is a gaming experience of high quality.", "hours": 93.4, "username": "Yureina", "products": 666, "early_access": false}
