{"product_id": "33230", "page": 488, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-07-31", "text": "Engaging story, exciting quests, and richness in variety. Assassin's Creed II has a beautiful interface and graphics, and is extremely user friendly. Definitely one of the best games I've ever played.", "hours": 59.6, "username": "moknah", "products": 282, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 488, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-07-30", "text": "The first Assassin's Creed was a joy to play. I stated in my review, though, that it felt like a disjointed collection of minigames.\nAssassin's Creed 2 (\"AC2\") takes those individual game elements from the first Assassin's Creed, and remixes them to create a game that's far more entertaining.\nFor this second game, the developers kept the stuff that works (climbing towers, free-running), and eliminated the things that were less fun (eavesdropping, picking pockets, long combat sequences). You're doing a better mix of stuff in AC2.\nThere are several indoor locations in this game, and the addition of storefronts on the city streets makes these Italian cities feel much more alive than the dusty, beautiful, barren cities of the first game.\nAC2 offers a variety of things for completionists to work at. Weapons and armor to purchase, art to collect from city merchants, Investments to be made in the infrastructure and services of the city around your family's villa. Feathers to collect from high city ledges, and a conspiracy theory to unravel. So many things to do! Bopping between them is great fun.\nThere are typical side-quests: assassinate so-and-so in service of your mentor, beat up someone's cheating husband, race through the city against a timer, deliver package from point A to point B. Yada yada yada.\nHowever, there are also a few exceptional sidequests in the guise of raiding underground tombs or Templar hideouts. These are masterful puzzles, in which you must make your way carefully through a maze of acrobatic leaps and climbs to obtain a special prize. This style of gameplay in AC2 is reminiscent of Mirror's Edge or Portal 2, in the way it challenges you to puzzle your way through an enclosed area that is reluctant to reveal its secrets. These special side quests each take about 45 minutes to complete. They were a high point of the game for me.\nI have two complaints. First, I would have preferred more stealth gameplay, and an option to complete the game without murdering hundreds of innocent city guards. Don't get me wrong; I found it very satisfying to pull an unsuspecting victim off a rampart and watch him fall to his death. But the body count is very high in this game, and the gratuitous murder sprees don't really mesh with the main character's \u201creluctant hero\u201d personality.\n\nMy other complaint with AC2 is its excessive length. The gameplay here is fun, but it doesn't change much over time. What you're doing in the 5th hour is very similar to what you're doing in the 30th hour. I spent over 40 hours in this game, and I was hoping for a finale after 20. This is a rare example of a game where too much of a good thing makes the overall experience less pleasurable, less memorable.\nBut don't let that stop you from playing. AC2 is frequently on sale for $5, and I can't think of many games that deliver better entertainment at any price.", "hours": 45.5, "username": "7grain", "products": 355, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 488, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-07-30", "text": "Best game in the Assassin's Creed series as of July 2013. Together with AC: Brotherhood, everyone should've tried these games out.", "hours": 61.2, "username": "lesderid", "products": 1014, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 488, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-07-29", "text": "AC2 is so many Desmond Miles ahead (puns!) of the first game, it stands solidly alone as its own title. While the PC controls aren't too shabby, it's best with a controller, and the visual fidelity from being on a PC is very much appreciated. With intuitive climbing, combat, and general all-around gameplay, AC2 has it all. Interesting side-stories, great, varied missions, wonderful characters, amazing levels and tactics, weaponry, voice acting, art style... they did their research. It's everything AC1 was and better. From score to story, graphics to even just the way you can slightly change cutscenes, buy new weapons, armor, dye it, build up your villa, and collectibles that have actual, story-based rewards and not just an achievement... Assassin's Creed 2 is a great, deep title. 10/10", "hours": 38.6, "username": "Fluff-Kevlar", "products": 518, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 488, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-07-27", "text": "Great step-up from the 1st with all the added elements but still true to the Creed ;)", "hours": 16.8, "username": "Zenith", "products": 1170, "early_access": false}
