{"product_id": "33230", "page": 505, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2012-12-12", "text": "Unlike it's predecessor, AC2 is strongly storydriven. There is no more stalking of your prey through sidequests and progress is handled solely through the story. Sidequests now simply have you do a specific task related to some of your skills.\nThis can work out, as it allows you to rush through and get the most out of the story, while still allowing you to partake in any particular activity. Want an assassination mission? Go find a pigeon stand and off you go.\nCombat-wise, AC2 is an overall improvement on everything. The dual blades work just as effective as you would imagine they have and you can buy your own weapons. Leaving you free choice over your main weapon, as well as your off-hand.\nBecause of how the story works, you'll always feel a sense of lineairity in the story. But since we are revisiting 'memories', this is perfectly excusable. And your approach to a combat situation is often left open anyway. You are free, within boundaries.\nThe landscapes and towns are a sight to behold, and the characters feel interesting too, albeit not enough explored by my taste. (save for Ezio)\nIf you don't mind an AC game that is more storydriven, it's worth buying to follow the story.", "hours": 34.1, "username": "il Duderoni", "products": 674, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 506, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2012-12-10", "text": "My favourite AC game of all time. Tops the first, Brotherhood, Revelations and AC3 by a long shot. Firenze and the other cities just feel much more alive than freaking Boston and New York (from AC3). Get AC2 today.", "hours": 51.4, "username": "Mr. Pro", "products": 616, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 506, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2012-12-10", "text": "Amazing and gripping storyline that leaves you on the edge of your chair waiting for more. Much better than the first AC; if you like adventure games this is definitely the game for you.\nP.S. You also get to be an assassin. :3", "hours": 28.3, "user_id": "76561197999507602", "username": "|\u00a2\u043a| d0gecoins", "products": 242, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 506, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2012-12-08", "text": "Perhaps the most interesting opus in the 4 first games (AC 1 to Revelations), and the best game of the saga with AC 3.", "hours": 6.8, "username": "[CPC] Koma Nouragan", "products": 890, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 506, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2012-12-05", "text": "This game was above average, expecially if you compare it to AC :D. AC2 didn't repeat itself like AC. You'll notice this when you play AC and AC2 through, because in AC you have three or four cities(don't remember) and there you have a little different looking buildings but the boring part is that missions in these cities even story, are 99% the same each time you do example; The assasination of  \"The bad guys\" is always the same no matter in what city you're currently terrorising the people.\nAC2 stands out in this part, beacause only few of the side missions are the same as in the other cities, but every story mission is unique...exept when you visit Leonardo...(Ezio, so good to see you. -Oh, I see that you've brought an another one. -Let's see, if i put this here and A-HA. etc.)\nI really enjoyed playing this game so much that I think i'm going to buy AC Brotherhood and Revelations, maybe AC3 afterwards :D.", "hours": 39.7, "username": "Conundrum", "products": 179, "early_access": false}
