{"product_id": "33230", "page": 548, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2011-02-19", "text": "The main thing in this game is its scenario base: all major history events turn out an endless fight between assassins and templars for so called \u201cPieces of Eden\u201d. Conspiracy, brutal violence, religious in its true shape, famous people in alternative reality \u2014 all runs through the entire game captivating till you see final credits. And, of course, it's all would be nothing without a good gameplay, where you run on the city roofs of Florence, Venice, Forli and Tuscany, killing guards with variety of weapons combining them. And yes \u2014 the game is freaking long.", "hours": 50.2, "username": "Joseph Stalin", "products": 497, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 548, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2011-02-18", "text": "Great open world with a crazy story and enough side missions to extend the story quite a bit!", "hours": 0.5, "username": "Nixon506E", "products": 520, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 548, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2011-02-15", "text": "Ezio... Italy, new game, new setting and a brand new game to explore the story that was developed in the first game. I believed it to be revolutionary, adding jump n run into an immersive, mostly open world, experience.\nYou are an elite Assasin, well that's nothing new I suppose, hunting down the traitors that have something to do with your personal life. Interested yet? You should be. I've could have not asked for a better world to statisfy my lust for silent but deadly stealth kills. Or just run in, jump up and stab them to hell in full view, so it caters for all kinds of killing lusts. Just don't expect a first person experience.\nGraphics have improved, controls are the same and you get the same package but a new story as the first one. Just right. Immersive story and interesting ending. You should give it a try, especially if you loved the first game.\n4.5 / 5", "hours": 25.4, "username": "Darkus Canning", "products": 418, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 548, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2011-02-15", "text": "Such an improvement over the first. If you can live with the DRM and the console loved woven throughout, this game is a great weekend in the making. With the semi-sequel, Brotherhood, just announced for PC release in March, this should be on special on Steam soon, hopefully.", "hours": 62.1, "user_id": "76561197992310231", "username": "HeyOldMate", "products": 218, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 548, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2011-02-14", "text": "Great story, great graphics, great palces, great characters, great gameplay, great music and sound, ... simply great.", "hours": 32.7, "username": "deer \u266a vs.  the World", "products": 621, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 548, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2011-02-12", "text": "An excellent sequel, keeping what worked and improving significantly what was not so great about the first game. Very long, great and varied missions, intriguing storyline.", "hours": 43.6, "username": "facls", "products": 663, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 548, "page_order": 8, "recommended": true, "date": "2011-02-11", "text": "The World's #1 Leonardo Da Vinci Buddy Simulator", "hours": 21.5, "username": "Waku", "products": 1148, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 548, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2011-02-09", "text": "You can't escape it. This game will easily suck days of your life away before it becomes boring. However, the only reason it becomes boring is because you feel invincible once you become practiced enough at the motions of fighting, and everyone knows how boring god-mode can become before long. Great story-line, acceptable cliff-hanger at the end with plenty of closer for one and plenty of opening suspense for another. Simply can not wait for the next.\nOh, and you get a renaissance pistol.", "hours": 77.5, "username": "Korvyr", "products": 286, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 549, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2011-02-08", "text": "Despite the DRM, you can't deny the awesomeness of this breathtaking game.", "hours": 42.2, "username": "\u2766 Piggy Pie \u2767", "products": 420, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 549, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2011-01-28", "text": "The first Assassin's Creed was a minor groundbreaker, heralding the return of the stealth genre and telling a multi-layered story within a wonderfully-realized world. Ultimately, however, the bland main character, sheer repetitiveness of the mission design, and abrupt ending kept a good game from achieving greatness. Fast forward two years, however, and Ubisoft Montreal had crafted Assassin's Creed II, a sequel that was superior to the original in every conceivable way. Moving from the middle east to Europe got rid of the monochromatic desert locales, giving way to vibrant cityscapes bustling with color, denizens, and side missions. That latter detail, along with the streamlined story structure, effectively eliminated the first game's biggest flaw. The main story path no longer consisted of having to perform the same mundane tasks over and over again to clear a path to the target. Each memory was now its own, self-contained concoction of writing, combat, and sneaking that added tangible weight to the player's actions. II also served to introduce the gaming world to Ezio Auditore, to this day the series' most beloved protagonist, as well as to famous faces from history that would become a series staple. Machiavelli, Pope Alexander the Sixth, and Leonardo Da Vinci each left impressions that characters from the first could only dream of. Even the present-day storyline got a face lift, fleshing out the characters to the point of acceptance by the majority of the players, as well as ending on a nail-biting cliffhanger that neatly paved the way for future installments. There may have been more bodies in the streets, but to this day, Assassin's Creed has never felt so alive.\nSCORE: 10/10", "hours": 50.2, "username": "StonedMagician", "products": 506, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 549, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2011-01-28", "text": "Great game, intense campaign and storyline, but really a one-time playthrough. Gorgous w/ maxed out settings, play it to 100% Completion!", "hours": 47.0, "user_id": "76561198031203343", "username": "slugcat", "products": 21, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 549, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2011-01-25", "text": "Great game, the gameplay is fun (much better than the first) and the story is an interesting retelling of history in the style of The Da Vinci Code (interestingly, Leonardo Da Vinci is one of the main characters here).\nI have two complaints: First, you have no control over saved games, and you cannot go back to replay any portion of the game without replaying the entire thing. Second, the game comes with some pretty lame DRM that requires you to be online at all times while playing.\nOther than that, its well worth playing and I'm looking forward to playing Assassin's Creed: Brotherhood when it comes out for PC.", "hours": 49.8, "username": "Jahandar", "products": 1171, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 549, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2011-01-25", "text": "If you liked the first one, you will like this.  If you didn't like the first one, you might like this too!   It is monumentally imrpoved over AC1, with a much more engaging plot and many more varied side-missions.  The AC2 world is gorgeous, and one of the most beautifully designed worlds I've seen in a video game (although the engine seems to enjoy rendering things as you walk past them :-\\  ).   I've also had zero trouble with the Ubisoft DRM stuff, so don't let that scare you away!", "hours": 36.3, "username": "Affidavit of Destruction", "products": 195, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 549, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2011-01-21", "text": "Really awesome game if you ignore the fact you gotta remember the photos for the keys, because the game feels like a console port.", "hours": 1.4, "username": "\uff9a\u0489.\u0320\u032a\u034e\u032f\u032e\u0364\u035b\u030b\u0300\u0346\u036e\u03107", "products": 730, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 549, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2011-01-20", "text": "Amazing Game! great graphics, gameplay was awesome.  A little tricky at first but once you get it the game gets that much better.  Different styles of assassination, different weapons, swords daggers throwing blades, refurbishing a city in the process, different armors, different variations of the colors for the armor.  5/5 Stars here", "hours": 87.6, "user_id": "76561198023050136", "username": "Benrett", "products": 211, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "33230", "page": 549, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2011-01-17", "text": "Great game. Action and movement was really fluid, great environments and story. Lots to explore.", "hours": 43.8, "username": "Columbus007", "products": 144, "early_access": false}
